On 01/03/11 7:07 PM, Russell Brown wrote:
> Hi,
> On Tue, 2011-03-01 at 18:02 +0530, Abhishek Kona wrote:
>> Hi folks
>>
>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after
>> running a test?
>> I am currently using the Java HTTP API.
> You can list the keys for the bucket and call delete for each. Or if you
> put the keys (and kept track of them in your test) you can delete them
> one at a time (without incurring the cost of calling list first.)
>
> Something like:
>
>          String bucket = "my_bucket";
>          BucketResponse bucketResponse = riakClient.listBucket(bucket);
>          RiakBucketInfo bucketInfo = bucketResponse.getBucketInfo();
>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {
>              riakClient.delete(bucket, key);
>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>
Sent from my iphone

>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after

>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {

>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>

On 01/03/11 7:07 PM, Russell Brown wrote:
> Hi,
> On Tue, 2011-03-01 at 18:02 +0530, Abhishek Kona wrote:
>> Hi folks
>>
>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after
>> running a test?
>> I am currently using the Java HTTP API.
> You can list the keys for the bucket and call delete for each. Or if you
> put the keys (and kept track of them in your test) you can delete them
> one at a time (without incurring the cost of calling list first.)
>
> Something like:
>
>          String bucket = "my_bucket";
>          BucketResponse bucketResponse = riakClient.listBucket(bucket);
>          RiakBucketInfo bucketInfo = bucketResponse.getBucketInfo();
>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {
>              riakClient.delete(bucket, key);
>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>

On 01/03/11 7:07 PM, Russell Brown wrote:
> Hi,
> On Tue, 2011-03-01 at 18:02 +0530, Abhishek Kona wrote:
>> Hi folks
>>
>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after
>> running a test?
>> I am currently using the Java HTTP API.
> You can list the keys for the bucket and call delete for each. Or if you
> put the keys (and kept track of them in your test) you can delete them
> one at a time (without incurring the cost of calling list first.)
>
> Something like:
>
>          String bucket = "my_bucket";
>          BucketResponse bucketResponse = riakClient.listBucket(bucket);
>          RiakBucketInfo bucketInfo = bucketResponse.getBucketInfo();
>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {
>              riakClient.delete(bucket, key);
>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>

Hi,

I am very interested in joining your influencer/pro program.

Through my company Adventure Architects, I am dedicated to bringing the heads of companies and their teams into the outdoors to partake in a variety of outdoor activities ranging from SUP'ing, rock climbing, sailing, yoga, outdoor dining, meditation, surfing, heli skiing, snow mobiling, glamping, etc. I built this company to allow me to personally host most of these experiencing while balancing the responsibilities of being a CEO of a fast growing company. We are dedicated to supporting sustainable practices internally and externally (educating our clients on everything from carbon-offsetting, recycling, opting out of one time use plastics, and nurturing a positive appreciation for the environment.

It's also worth drawing attention to the community groups that we service (Summit.co & https://drive.google.com/file/d/1bAPbUG_OmBstmmgY63ELsigAV_DoVceJ/view , thebatterysf.com & WeWork). I believe these could be compelling for you as they create diverse exposure to an affluent user group who opt-in to have premium outdoor experiences and I imagine are well placed to become your customers. The most compelling of the group is probably the summit community for whom I personally host a variety of outdoor/active experiences in Tulum, at Summit Powder Mountain and Los Angeles. Take a look at the deck I linked above.

Additionally, I volunteer as a cadet with Marin Search and Rescue. With approximately sixty active members, Marin County's Search and Rescue (Marin SAR) responds to searches for missing children and adults, evidence and other search requests in the county and on mutual aid calls anywhere in the state of California. Marin SAR is a mountain rescue Type I team with the motto of: "Anytime, Anywhere, Any Weather." We just got back last night after 3 days of searching the Trinity Alps for missing hiker.

As an outdoor professional, I am always on the hunt for apparel and gear that lives at the intersection of functionality and style. I believe your products do just that and it would be an honor to rep your company in front of our audience.  - carina.hessmer@gmail.com

On 01/03/11 7:07 PM, Russell Brown wrote:
> Hi,
> On Tue, 2011-03-01 at 18:02 +0530, Abhishek Kona wrote:
>> Hi folks
>>
>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after
>> running a test?
>> I am currently using the Java HTTP API.
> You can list the keys for the bucket and call delete for each. Or if you
> put the keys (and kept track of them in your test) you can delete them
> one at a time (without incurring the cost of calling list first.)
>
> Something like:
>
>          String bucket = "my_bucket";
>          BucketResponse bucketResponse = riakClient.listBucket(bucket);
>          RiakBucketInfo bucketInfo = bucketResponse.getBucketInfo();
>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {
>              riakClient.delete(bucket, key);
>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>

>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after

>> I am currently using the Java HTTP API.
> You can list the keys for the bucket and call delete for each. Or if you
> put the keys (and kept track of them in your test) you can delete them

>
> Something like:
>
>          String bucket = "my_bucket";
>          BucketResponse bucketResponse = riakClient.listBucket(bucket);
>          RiakBucketInfo bucketInfo = bucketResponse.getBucketInfo();
>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {
>              riakClient.delete(bucket, key);
>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>

On 01/03/11 7:07 PM, Russell Brown wrote:
> Hi,
> On Tue, 2011-03-01 at 18:02 +0530, Abhishek Kona wrote:
>> Hi folks
>>
>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after
>> running a test?
>> I am currently using the Java HTTP API.
> You can list the keys for the bucket and call delete for each. Or if you
> put the keys (and kept track of them in your test) you can delete them
> one at a time (without incurring the cost of calling list first.)
>
> Something like:
>
>          String bucket = "my_bucket";
>          BucketResponse bucketResponse = riakClient.listBucket(bucket);
>          RiakBucketInfo bucketInfo = bucketResponse.getBucketInfo();
>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {
>              riakClient.delete(bucket, key);
>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>
Sent from my iphone

On 01/03/11 7:07 PM, Russell Brown wrote:
> Hi,
> On Tue, 2011-03-01 at 18:02 +0530, Abhishek Kona wrote:
>> Hi folks
>>
>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after
>> running a test?
>> I am currently using the Java HTTP API.
> You can list the keys for the bucket and call delete for each. Or if you
> put the keys (and kept track of them in your test) you can delete them
> one at a time (without incurring the cost of calling list first.)
>
> Something like:
>
>          String bucket = "my_bucket";
>          BucketResponse bucketResponse = riakClient.listBucket(bucket);
>          RiakBucketInfo bucketInfo = bucketResponse.getBucketInfo();
>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {
>              riakClient.delete(bucket, key);
>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>

On 01/03/11 7:07 PM, Russell Brown wrote:
> Hi,
> On Tue, 2011-03-01 at 18:02 +0530, Abhishek Kona wrote:
>> Hi folks
>>
>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after
>> running a test?
>> I am currently using the Java HTTP API.
> You can list the keys for the bucket and call delete for each. Or if you
> put the keys (and kept track of them in your test) you can delete them
> one at a time (without incurring the cost of calling list first.)
>
> Something like:
>
>          String bucket = "my_bucket";
>          BucketResponse bucketResponse = riakClient.listBucket(bucket);
>          RiakBucketInfo bucketInfo = bucketResponse.getBucketInfo();
>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {
>              riakClient.delete(bucket, key);
>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>

On 01/03/11 7:07 PM, Russell Brown wrote:
> Hi,
> On Tue, 2011-03-01 at 18:02 +0530, Abhishek Kona wrote:
>> Hi folks
>>
>> What is the best way to clear a Riak bucket of all key, values after
>> running a test?
>> I am currently using the Java HTTP API.
> You can list the keys for the bucket and call delete for each. Or if you
> put the keys (and kept track of them in your test) you can delete them
> one at a time (without incurring the cost of calling list first.)
>
> Something like:
>
>          String bucket = "my_bucket";
>          BucketResponse bucketResponse = riakClient.listBucket(bucket);
>          RiakBucketInfo bucketInfo = bucketResponse.getBucketInfo();
>
>          for(String key : bucketInfo.getKeys()) {
>              riakClient.delete(bucket, key);
>          }
>
>
> would do it.
>
> See also
>
> http://wiki.basho.com/REST-API.html#Bucket-operations
>
